Note:
 - the HVAC actuator is learnt to sender address 0x17111976. This correct address is used at every 3rd packet only, otherwise the wrong sender address ending with 0x77 is used.
 - the learning is done using 4BS teach-in in Variation 3 (according EnOcean EEP document, appendix). Thus, both sides should also store the Sender-ID.
 - the HVAC actuator requests its new position and expects this to be given in the response packet. In the request packet it also sends its current position (CV) as the first data byte, which allows to determine whether the command in the answer was accepted or not.
 - the target address of the response packet 0x05060708 in the test does not match the HVAC address 0xffd57800.
 - the HVAC actuator has an automatic polling each 10 minutes but also a polling on request (via a button on the actuator). This button was used for the tests. If the button is used, it sends the request twice, in automatic polling only once (I don't know why).
 - it takes a few seconds for the actuator to set the new desired position, because of this the CV is shown delayed.

What you see is:
 - the HVAC actuator follows the given target position in the first byte (you can also hear the motor moving) for each packet provided, independent on addressing. The packet just needs to come within one second after the request.

My conclusions:
This Micropelt HVAC actuator is not working as it should. As far as I know, it is a very new product and my devices are test samples form the manufacturer. I will also raise this question to Micropelt.

