Just to be clear, `ObjectBase` does not try/except it away - it's python's `object` class that does this in it's `__getattribute__` - when a class has `__getattr__` defined, this is the behavior:

    class A(object):
        @property
        def f(self):
            return self.g

        def __getattr__(self, name):
            raise AttributeError(name + '!!!')

    print(A().f)

it is standard python behavior and that's why I am reluctant to "fix" it. The fix would also contain modifying the object's `__getattribute__` instead of `__getattr__` which is potentially dangerous and can have some performance implications. I will run some tests and see what the difference would be if it's worth it.

