@mcg1969 has your re-working of conda and perhaps "clone" addressed the other issue I raise about package plans, and the behavior when "offline" if the plan has identified the need to download?

 @kalefranz do you have a perspective on this issue or its importance/priority?

@ukoethe : to be clear, right now conda does not enforce any previous package dependencies.  The only thing you are (currently) guaranteed to have as "satisfied dependencies" are the last conda install command you invoked.  Think of it as `autoconf + deps`: if you go and do `./configure && make && sudo make install` you have no guarantees that this won't have broken a stack of other things that used the previous version of the software that you have just overwritten by your latest `autoconf`-based install sequence.  Conda gives you that experience without compilation and with the addition of dependencies being automatically fetched and installed.

@mcg1969 and @groutr the main problem we're going to have with this is that everyone currently has "old-style" environments where dependencies were not preserved.  I just installed conda from the `rgrout` channel and now I can't install anything else, AFAICT, since I get about 2 dozen conflicts.

And this emphasizes my point for @ukoethe : these supposed conflicts that are being reported really aren't conflicts that will result in brokenness: I know that my package will work just fine if it is installed, and that other things will be **no more broken** than they already are due to already violated dependencies resulting from installing the latest package.  The analogy I used elsewhere is that of dead hyperlinks: the web works because we don't enforce referential integrity.  Likewise, an operating system requires all package dependencies to be satisfied at all times or important things can be critically broken, however conda package dependencies are often too strict and enforcing them will prevent a user from installing packages in ways that **typically* won't break other things in the conda environment.  We need to allow "broken links".

