Here is also something else to ponder:

Since this patch is currently rather invasive (and seems to be getting more so in every iteration :)), I'm also wondering if there are other use cases that might justify merging it. One of them are implicit conversions for C++ multiple inheritance. It could be that your work is already directly applicable to that problem as well, and that would be simply fantastic.

The trouble with multiple inheritance is that an instance of a type ``A`` can't easily be converted to an instance of, say, type ``G`` (with the following classes shown below), because the implicit ``this`` pointer needs to be shifted around while traversing the graph of classes. C++ does this automatically because it knows about the involved types, but pybind11 has no such feature at the moment.

```
A : public B, C { };
B : public D, E { };
C : public F, G { };

class G { void f(); };
```

My thought was that the pybind11 ``class_<>`` setup code for a polymorphic class with multiple inheritance could register a CPP implicit conversion for all of its base classes, i.e.:

```
register_implicitly_convertible<A, B>();
register_implicitly_convertible<A, C>();
register_implicitly_convertible<B, D>();
register_implicitly_convertible<B, E>();
register_implicitly_convertible<C, F>();
register_implicitly_convertible<C, G>();
```

When a method ``G::f()`` is called with an ``A`` instance, my hope was that the recursive implicit conversion code would cause these conversions to take place by running the conversion from ``A`` to ``C`` and then from ``C`` to ``G`` (it would be no problem if that happens in a sort of brute force manner, which tries out some invalid conversions as well)

What do you think? (Note that this is not a request for you to go and implement multiple inheritance ;) but rather a question on whether this PR could be a part of a bigger project)

